@node utils
                              ON DISK UTILITIES

On this disk are two P.D utilities called Filemaster and GrabIFF
to get to these we need to use Workbench.
If you have a hard drive you can boot up your system and then insert
the tutorial disk read below on what to do then.  
If you do not have a hard drive we will need to load you up a small 
Workbench for you. If you remember, when you boot this disk
you get asked a question 'See on disk utils y/n' to get here you would
of answered "n", well all you need to do is answer 'y' and a mini 
Workbench will be loaded for you.

Follow these steps to access the programs:

* Turn off your Amiga and make sure ABGTWB3_VOL1 is in the internal
  disk drive.
* Switch on your Amiga (This is called booting a disk)
* Answer 'y' to the see utils question.
* A Workbench will then load. 
* Double click on the disk icon called 'ABGTWB3_VOL1'
* A window will appear with some icons in it.
* Double click on the drawer icon called 'PD_UTILS'
* Now double click on any one of the four icons that appear
  in the new window that has been opened.
* Filemaster.Doc and GrabIFF.Doc are the instructions on how to use
  each program, just double click on the icon and a text displayer
  will load up the text and display it, press the Escape key when you 
  have finished reading a doc file.
* Double click on 'Filemaster' or 'GrabIFF' to run either program.

NOTE: You can double click on 'Menus.Guide' to load this guide.

@{" Return to main menu " link main}

@endnode

@node vby
                                   VIEW BY
                                   -------
View By, lets you control the appearance of files in your @{" windows " link window} in 
four different ways:

Icons,   This is the default setting where only files with an associated 
         @{" icon " link icon} are displayed, all other files are hidden from view.
         Click on this @{" diagram " system " showpic vby_icon.iff"} of View By/Icon.

By Name, Displays ALL files from the current directory in alphabetical 
         order in text form, no icons are displayed at all.
         Click on this @{" diagram " system " showpic vby_name.iff"} of View By/Name.

By Date, Displays ALL files in chronological order, files have date stamps
         in them, only any use if you have a built in clock really. 
         Displayed in text form.
         Click on this @{" diagram " system " showpic vby_date.iff"} of View By/date.

By Size, Displays ALL files, sorts the file list by size starting with the
         smallest file listed first,of limited use. Displayed in text form.
         Click on this @{" diagram " system " showpic vby_size.iff"} of View By/Size.

QUICK GUIDE IN PLAIN ENGLISH
----------------------------
* Make sure an open @{" window " link window} is @{" selected " link mouse}.
* Hold down the right mouse button,
* Move the mouse pointer to the Window @{" menu " link menu} at the top of the screen.
* @{" Highlight " link highlight} VIEW BY. 
* Choose between the four options in the sub-menu, and then release right 
  mouse button.
@endnode


@node show
                                     SHOW
                                     ----
In normal, everyday use, using the default @{" Workbench " link workbench} setting of 
showing @{ " icons " link icon} only is fine, it saves a lot of useless files 
being displayed and cluttering up the screen. Any file that does not have 
an .info file associated with it will not be displayed in this mode.
As an example I have copied three files to the @{" Ram Disk " link ram disk}, they are:

Clock
Clock.info
invaders

When I @{" Double click " link mouse} on the Ram Disk icon the Clock will be 
displayed on the screen because it has an icon associated 
with it, (the .info file) Where as Invaders will not be visible as it has
no .info file (icon). So, what happens if you wanted to run the Invaders 
program? (Assuming you already knew it was there of course) There are a few
courses of action you could take. You could start the Invaders program from
the @{" Shell " link shell}. You could start it using the @{" Execute Command " link xcom}
option from the Workbench menu.  Or, probably the easiest, you could select
SHOW and in the @{" sub-menu " link menu} select ALL FILES, this will display ALL the 
FILES in the current directory wether they have icons or not, you can then
double click on ANY file and try to run it.

Look at this @{" diagram " system " showpic show_all.iff"} of Show/All Files and this @{" diagram " system " showpic show_icons.iff"} 
of Show/Icons Only.

QUICK GUIDE IN PLAIN ENGLISH
----------------------------
* Make sure an open @{" window " link window} is @{" selected " link mouse}.
* Hold down the right mouse button,
* Move the mouse pointer to the Window @{" menu " link menu} at the top of the screen.
* @{" Highlight " link highlight} SHOW 
* Choose between ONLY ICONS or ALL FILES, and release right mouse button.

@endnode


@node sshot
