@node cleanup
                                   CLEAN UP
                                   --------
This is an extremely handy option, use it regularly. Personally I would
of called it TIDY UP, but there you go! What it does is rearrange the 
@{" icons " link icon} of the currently selected @{" window " link window}, simple as that, 
but effective.
Take a look at this @{" diagram " system " showpic clean_up.iff"} and you will understand.

QUICK GUIDE IN PLAIN ENGLISH
----------------------------
* @{" Double click " link mouse} on a disk icon to @{" open " link open} it.
* Hold down the right mouse button,
* Move the mouse pointer to the Window @{" menu " link menu} at the top of the screen.
* @{" Highlight " link highlight} CLEAN UP and then release the right mouse button.
* Any icons in the window will now be tidied up.

FURTHER INFORMATION
-------------------
If you want the icons to stay in the new tidied position see @{" snapshot " link sshot}.
Keyboard @{" short-cut " link shortcut} is: Hold down the right Amiga key 
and press '.' 
@endnode
@node sconts
                               SELECT CONTENTS
                               ---------------
To select or @{" highlight " link mouse} an @{" icon " link icon} you need to @{" click " link mouse} on it once 
with the left mouse button. 

But say you wanted to select a lot of icons all at once for an operation? 
For example, let's say you had sixty files on a floppy disk and that you 
wanted to @{" delete " link delete} fifty of them. You could approach this in one of 
four ways: 

1) You could @{" format " link format} the entire disk, no good because you would lose
   the ten files you wanted to keep.
2) You could select each icon one at a time then select delete from the 
   icons menu, very time consuming indeed.
3) You could hold shift down and click on all fifty icons making them all
   selected and then select delete, still a big job.
4) Or you do the right thing and use SELECT CONTENTS, this would select
   all sixty icons, you could then de-select the ten files you wanted to 
   keep by clicking on them once with the left mouse button and then do a 
   delete from the icons menu to get rid of the fifty that would remain 
   selected.

As you may have gathered, SELECT CONTENTS highlights the whole contents of
the currently selected @{" window " link window}.

@{"Click here to see diagram " system " showpic scontents.iff"} for diagram. 

FURTHER INFORMATION
-------------------
If you want to @{" drag " link mouse} all of the selected files somewhere you will need 
to hold the shift key down first.

Keyboard @{" short-cut " link shortcut} is: Hold down the right Amiga key and press A
@endnode


@node update
                                    UPDATE
                                    ------
This is the baby brother of @{" Update All "link udall} found in the Workbench menu.
Where UPDATE differs from Update All is that it only updates the selected
@{" Window " link window} and so is faster.
If you make changes to the contents of a window through the @{" Shell " link shell}
or the @{" Execute Command " link xcom} menu item, you may not be able to see 
any changes you have made unless you close and re-open that window. 
Selecting UPDATE will UPDATE the contents of the Window without you having 
to close & re-open it. It's a matter of personal preference, personally I
find it faster to open and close the window myself. 

QUICK GUIDE IN PLAIN ENGLISH
----------------------------
* @{" Double click " link mouse} on a disk @{" icon " link icon} to @{" open " link open} it.
* Hold down the right mouse button,
* Move the mouse pointer to the Window @{" menu " link menu} at the top of the screen.
* @{" Highlight " link highlight} UPDATE and then release the right mouse button.
* The window will now be updated and any changes made to it will appear.

@{" View diagram " system " showpic update.iff"} for diagram. 
@endnode


@node Close
                                    CLOSE
                                    -----
Virtually the same as @{" Open Parent " link oparent} except this closes the
currently selected @{" window " link window}.  
It's a lot easier and quicker to just use each window's CLOSE gadget, 
located at the top left of any window, click on it once with the left mouse
button.

QUICK GUIDE IN PLAIN ENGLISH
----------------------------
* @{" Double click " link mouse} on a disk @{" icon " link icon} to @{" open " link open} it.
* Hold down the right mouse button,
* Move the mouse pointer to the Window @{" menu " link menu} at the top of the screen.
* @{" Highlight " link highlight} CLOSE and then release the right mouse button.
* The window will now close.

@{"Click on me " system " showpic close.iff"} for diagram. 

Keyboard @{" short-cut " link shortcut} is: Hold down the right Amiga key and press K

@endnode



@node oparent
                                 OPEN PARENT
                                 -----------
OPEN PARENT isn't an option you should worry about too much. Basically it 
allows you to step back through nested directories and @{" drawers " link drawers} if 
you get in a tangle. For example, you may have opened a drawer and inside 
that there is another drawer and inside that another drawer and inside 
that...etc.  Using OPEN PARENT you can step back a directory at a time.
Realistically it's a lot easier and quicker to just use each @{" windows " link window} 
@{" close " link close} gadget, located at the top left of any window. 

QUICK GUIDE IN PLAIN ENGLISH
----------------------------
* Presuming you have at least one drawer @{" open " link open}:
* Hold down the right mouse button,
* Move the mouse pointer to the Window @{" menu " link menu} at the top of the screen.
* @{" Highlight " link mouse} OPEN PARENT and then release the right mouse button.
* The drawer window should @{" close " link close}.

@{"Click on me " system " showpic oparent.iff"} for diagram. 
@endnode


@node newdrawer
                                  NEW DRAWER
                                  ----------
This is a very useful option, it allows you to easily create a new 
@{" drawer " link drawers} on any disk, complete with an @{" icon " link icon} and your choice of name.

QUICK GUIDE IN PLAIN ENGLISH
----------------------------
* @{" Double click " link mouse} on the disk icon of the disk you wish to create 
  the new drawer on.
* If necessary, double click inside a previously made drawer, 
  if you want to create a sub drawer.
* Hold down the right mouse button,
* Move the mouse pointer to the @{" Window " link window} menu at the top of the screen.
* @{" Highlight " link highlight} NEW DRAWER and then release the right mouse button.
* In the requester that will now appear, type in a new name or leave the 
  default name in, which is called Unnamed1.
* Click on Ok or press return.
* The new drawer is now created, complete with icon.

@{"Click on me " system " showpic newdrawer.iff"} for diagram. 

FURTHER INFORMATION
-------------------
You can create as many drawers as you want, space permitting.

You can create drawers inside drawers, nested as much as you want.

You can use @{" Rename " link rename} to rename any drawer.

If you @{" delete " link delete} a drawer you will automatically delete all of its 
contents, including sub-drawers and their contents.

If you @{" drag " link mouse} a drawer to another part of the disk, or even
to another disk completely, all the drawers contents, including sub-drawers
and their contents will also be copied.

If you create more than one new drawer on a disk and are using the default
name of Unnamed1 then the Amiga automatically makes the next drawer name
Unnamed2, Unnamed3 etc.

Keyboard @{" short-cut " link shortcut} is: Hold down the right Amiga key and press N
@endnode

