@node path
                               WHAT IS A PATH?
                                -------------
A path, as far as the Amiga and most other computers are concerned, is 
a route leading to the location of a desired file.

Straight into some examples:

Let's say you have a blank disk and you have @{" named " link rename} the blank disk 
'MY_DISK'. Then you @{" copied " link copy} a file called 'FRED.TXT' onto it. 
The path for 'FRED.TXT' would be:

MY_DISK:FRED.TXT 

It doesn't matter what disk drive MY_DISK is in as you have called the disk
by name. You could also of called the path:

DF0:FRED.TXT 

In this case you are telling the Amiga that the file FRED.TXT is on the
disk in the internal drive. 
If you wanted to use the external drive (DF1:) you could use:

DF1:FRED.TXT

It's probably best to use the actual name of the disk if you can though.

Remember that after the disks name you MUST put a colon (:) this tells
the Amiga that you mean a device, which means a peripheral like a drive
or printer etc.

Now supposing 'FRED.TXT' was inside a drawer called 'LETTER' on 'MY_DISK'?

MY_DISK:LETTERS/FRED.TXT

would work perfectly. The '/' tells the Amiga to look in a drawer.

What about sub-directories then?

MY_DISK:TEXT_FILES/LETTERS/FRED.TXT

and so on.

Most decent programs on the Amiga let you select a programs path by giving
you a file requester (we will look at file requesters next volume), 
where all you have to do is locate the file and @{" click " link mouse} on
it. Alternatively, running most programs will simply mean double clicking 
on the programs @{" icon " link icon}, so don't worry too much about this
sort of thing if you are still learning.
@endnode
@node shell
                              WHAT IS THE SHELL?
                              ------------------
I would have to write a whole book to cover this subject properly and 
indeed there are books out there that cover the shell. For this tutorial 
though I will just give you a fleeting glimpse of how to use the shell. 
As this guide is primarily meant for absolute beginners I wouldn't want to 
go too far anyway, it would probably confuse rather than help most 
beginners.

So in a nut shell (pun, fully intended) the SHELL program can be found in 
the System drawer of your @{" Workbench " link workbench} disk. @{" Double click " link mouse} 
on the SHELL @{" icon " link icon} and a @{" window " link window} will open and a cursor 
will await your command. 
Here is a more graphical @{" explanation " system " showpic shell.iff"} of the shell.

When you have finished with the shell you can get rid of it by clicking the
